        <div xml:id="AN2-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN2">
            <lg type="edition"><l><choice><seg>kōḻilai</seg><seg>kōḷilai</seg></choice> vāḻaik <choice><seg>kōṇmutir</seg><seg>kōṇmiku</seg></choice> peruṅkulai</l>
<l><choice><seg>yūḻuṟu</seg><seg>pūḻuṟu</seg></choice> tīṅkaṉi yuṇṇunart taṭutta</l>
<l>cāraṟ palaviṉ cuḷaiyō ṭūḻpaṭupu</l>
<l>pāṟai neṭuñcuṉai viḷainta tē<supplied>ṟa</supplied></l>
<l>la<supplied>ṟi</supplied>yā tuṇṭa kaṭuva ṉayalatu</l>
<l>kaṟivaḷar cānta mēṟal collātu</l>
<l>naṟuvī yaṭukkattu makiḻntukaṇ paṭukkuṅ</l>
<l>ku<supplied>ṟi</supplied>yā viṉpa <choice><seg>meḷiteṉa</seg><seg>meḷiti</seg></choice> <choice><seg>niṉmalaip</seg><seg>ṉiṉmalaip</seg></choice></l>
<l>palvēṟu vilaṅku meytu nāṭa</l>
<l>kuṟitta viṉpa niṉakkeva ṉariya</l>
<l>veṟutta vē<supplied>e</supplied>r <choice><seg>vēypurai</seg><seg>vēymaruḷ</seg></choice> paṇaittō</l>
<l><choice><seg>ṇiṟuppa</seg><seg>ṇiṟukka</seg></choice> nillā neñcamoṭu niṉmāṭ</l>
<l>ṭivaḷu miṉaiya ḷāyiṟ ṟantai</l>
<l>yaruṅkaṭik kāvalar cōrpata ṉoṟṟik</l>
<l>kaṅkul varutalu muriyai paimputal</l>
<l>vēṅkaiyu moḷḷiṇar virintaṉa</l>
<l>neṭuveṇ ṭiṅkaḷu mūrkoṇ ṭaṉṟē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>On the slope,</l>
<l>that <choice><seg>wards off </seg><seg>wards off the </seg></choice> eaters <choice><seg>from </seg><seg>of </seg></choice> <choice><seg>the overripe </seg><seg>the </seg></choice> sweet <choice><seg>fruit</seg><seg>fruit with holes</seg></choice> </l>
<l>in big <choice><seg>bundles that mature </seg><seg>bundles, growing </seg></choice> <choice><seg>in bunches on </seg><seg>in bunches on the </seg></choice> plantains <choice><seg>with rich </seg><seg>with </seg></choice> <choice><seg>fronds,</seg><seg>fronds in bunches,</seg></choice> </l>
<l>the male monkey, that has unwittingly drunk</l>
<l rend="indent">	the liquor ripened in the long mountain pool by the rocks</l>
<l rend="indent">	after having fermented from the pulp of the jack-fruit,</l>
<l>without speaking<note place="foot">Here the unequivocal collātu preserved by the palm-leaf mss. has been silently emended into cellātu from the later paper copies onwards, upon the assumption that monkeys do not speak.  However, if they may commit suicide out of grief, as in Kuṟuntokai 69, I do not feel this reason is sufficient for altering the transmitted text.</note> of climbing the pepper-grown sandal tree in the neighbourhood,</l>
<l>closes [its] eyes joyfully on the mountain-side with fragrant blossoms.</l>
<l>O man from a land where many different animals approach</l>
<l>your <choice><seg>mountain, thinking “easy is </seg><seg>mountain easily, for </seg></choice> the unintended <choice><seg>pleasure”,</seg><seg>pleasures...</seg></choice> </l>
<l>what [are] the rare pleasures intended by you?</l>
<l>[She with] broad shoulders resembling bamboo with ample beauty,</l>
<l>if she too is like this</l>
<l rend="indent">	on your account, with a heart that does not stop pondering,</l>
<l>you have the right to come at night too, making use</l>
<l>of the moment [her]father’s fiercely protective watchmen doze off.</l>
<l>Bright clusters have expanded on the kino tree by the fresh bushes</l>
<l>and the long white moon has crept up.<note place="foot">ūr-koṇṭaṉṟu: for koḷ as an auxiliary, and possibly already in reflexive function, cf. KT 377.4f.: ...nāṭaṉoṭu | ceytu koṇṭatōr ciṟu nal naṭpē, “good little intimacy that has been made with the man from the land.”</note></l>
<l>17b and the long white moon has taken the village.</l></lg>
        </div>
